Create Project:
cds init --add nodejs incident-management

To Create SAP Fiori App:
Command Platter(Ctrl+Shift+P) -> Fiori: Open Application Generator -> List Report Page -> Use ocal Cap Project, choose other ->

Run SAP Fiori:
Command Platter(Ctrl+Shift+P) -> Fiori: Open Application Info -> Preview Application -> npm run watch-incidents(second one)

SAP Fiori Launch page:
To launch Preview Application
https://port4004-workspaces-ws-9pkk5.us10.trial.applicationstudio.cloud.sap/launchpage.html#Shell-home

Add tests dependencies:
npm add -D @cap-js/cds-test

To add an SAP HANA Cloud client to your application:
cds add hana --for production

1. Prepare for Production(https://developers.sap.com/tutorials/prep-for-prod.html):
    Add SAP HANA Cloud:
    $ cds add hana --for production

    inspect the effective production configuration:
    $ cds env requires -4 production

    1. Configure the SAP Authorization and Trust Management service:
    $ cds add xsuaa --for production

    2. Make sure that the SAP Authorization and Trust Management configuration has been added to the package.json file:
    {
    "name": "incident-management",
    "dependencies": {
        ...
        "@sap/xssec": "^x"
    },
    ...
    "cds": {
        "requires": {
        ...
        "[production]": {
            "db": "hana",
            "auth": "xsuaa"
        }
        ...
        }
    }
    }

    3. Check the content of the xs-security.json file.

    Add configuration for SAP Build Work Zone, standard edition:
    $ cds add workzone-standard

    Check the content of the app/incidents/package.json file:
    package.json: 
        "destinations": true,
        "html5-repo": true,
        "workzone": true

    Check the newly created file ui5-deploy.yaml in the folder app/incidents/.
    Verify that the navigation target incidents-display and the SAP Cloud service sap.cloud have been correctly added to the application manifest file app/incidents/webapp/manifest.json:
    Open app/incidents/webapp/manifest.json and remove the leading / from the uri parameter.

    In the terminal, navigate to the app/incidents/ folder and run the following command:
    npm install

    Run a test build:
    $ cds build --production
    output like:
    [cds] - build completed in 511 ms
